# TypeScript Coding Standards

## Immutability (CRITICAL)

ALWAYS create new objects, NEVER mutate existing ones:

```typescript
// WRONG: mutation
function updateUser(user: User, name: string): User {
  user.name = name;
  return user;
}

// CORRECT: immutable update
function updateUser(user: Readonly<User>, name: string): User {
  return { ...user, name };
}
```

## Types and Interfaces

- Add explicit types to exported functions, services, and public APIs
- Let TypeScript infer obvious local variable types
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections/utilities
- Prefer string literal unions over `enum`
- NEVER use `any` — use `unknown` for untrusted input, then narrow

```typescript
// WRONG
function getErrorMessage(error: any) { return error.message; }

// CORRECT
function getErrorMessage(error: unknown): string {
  return error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unexpected error';
}
```

## File Organization

- 200-400 lines typical, 800 max
- One component/service/controller per file
- Organize by feature, not by type
- Extract utilities from large modules

## Error Handling

- Handle errors explicitly at every level
- Use async/await with try-catch
- Log detailed context server-side, user-friendly messages client-side
- Never silently swallow errors
- No `console.log` in production — use proper logging

## Input Validation

- Validate all user input at system boundaries
- Backend: use class-validator DTOs
- Frontend: validate before API calls
- Never trust external data

## Code Quality Checklist

Before marking work complete:
- [ ] Functions are small (<50 lines)
- [ ] Files are focused (<800 lines)
- [ ] No deep nesting (>4 levels)
- [ ] Proper error handling
- [ ] No hardcoded values (use constants or config)
- [ ] No mutation (immutable patterns used)
- [ ] No `any` types
- [ ] No `console.log`
